value.0: A scowl playing across her broad, stern face, this woman marches toward you. Her skin is gray and tight, somehow reminding you of deadwood half-buried in the sand.
She plants her feet and crosses her arms. "Ye have some nerve, barging into a woman's home, interrupting her from her weaving. Why, when me husband comes home..."
Her arms crossed firmly beneath her bosom, the woman shows no sign of budging. "If it's answers ye want, then go pester Helga in the Guild Hall. This be a private home."

value.0: <StartAction>[DC: 12]</Start> Choose a Fooling tactic.
<StartAction>[Failure]</Start> The woman glowers at you. "Don't ye be trying your petty spells on me, <mister/missus>. Now get out."
<StartAction>[Success]</Start> The woman's eyes glaze over. "Of course, he already knows you... I'm sorry, come in. How can I help you?"
<StartAction>[Invalid Tactic]</Start> Sorry, you are currently unable to cast Charm Person.
<StartAction>[Success]</Start> "Ah, I be sorry, m'<Lord/Lady>. It's been a stressful day with me husband doing Council business. How can I help you serve him?"
<StartAction>[Failure]</Start> Her eyebrows pull together, the eyes beneath them seeming to take on a darker tone. "Don't ye take me for a fool. Leave these halls at once!"
<StartAction>[Success]</Start> The woman blushes, some welcome color coming to her pale gray features. "Of course. I'm sorry. How can I help ye while we wait?"
She marches right up to you, thrusting her stout finger into your chest. "Out. There still be weaving to be done before me husband returns."
The woman shakes her head in frustration. "And good riddance."
"Then go ask your questions at the Guild Hall. Ye'll learn more there than I be ever telling you. How many time do I have to tell ye I've got weaving to be done!?"
"He be an important member of the Guild Council and owner of the old mine next door. Why that mine still employs most of the village! There, that be more than ye deserve to know, so shoo!"
"One too many, that's for sure. Now leave me alone."
"Aye, well ye not be alone, it seems. Ye can ask me husband about that, now get out!"

Her harsh countenance softens as she approaches. "If ye continue to interrupt me weaving, I shan't finish it before me husband returns. But no matter now, I welcome the company. What can I do for ye?"
"We be Barrow Dwarves here, and proud of it. The last of Brogan's own clan, carving our existence out of the northlands, living on the surface, not hiding down inside the rock."
"Nothing good comes from below. Even me husband's mine, it travels far, just below the surface. It don't go deep. Ever since Brogan returned up from the underworld, the rocks be haunted."
"Barrow Dwarves, Cairn Dwarves, Sons of Brogan. Look, if ye be that interested, I recommend you pay a visit to the Guild Hall."
"He be an important member of the Guild Council and owner of the old mine next door. Though the ore be fading, that mine still employs almost all the clan."

The woman ponders her sausage-like hands. "Not as big as it be in Brogan's times. This village be almost all that's left. There be other clans elsewhere but Brogan's own is slowly fading from the world."
"The wooden building right next door. It caps a shaft into the mines below. There was a time when there were gems the size of me fist down there, but no longer. Now we mine mostly for iron."
"It be our ruling body here in Brogan's Arm, composed mainly of clan elders and the like. If ye be that interested in it, there be all manner of such information available in the Guild Hall."
"Yes, a group of maybe fifty or so passed through yesterday. I never saw them meself but me husband said they be knights from some distant order to the south."
"Apparently they headed up north through the pass. They'd come to see the Night Hag, I suppose, though goodness knows why. Every now and then, though, folks come through asking of her."
The woman stretches, shifting her weight to the other foot. In the new light, you can see dark bags beginning to form under her eyes.
The dwarf ponders this for a moment. "No doubt the Guild Council would know something of it. If ye be that interested, ye might want to ask Helga over at the Guild Hall."
"She be a witch, constantly coming down from her cemetery in the pass to sell her filthy rags. We dwarves steer well clear of her where we can and ye'd be wise to do the same."
The woman scowls at you in disgust. "Oh, I don't buy them, no <sir/madam>. No doubt she steals them from the corpses of the dead, wretched creature, living in that cemetery as she does."
"The Cavanaugh Stone? At the Barrow site? The Guild Council came by in the storm last night, calling for me husband and saying there was trouble at the stone. He hasn't been back since."
The woman eyes gives you a weary look. It's obvious she hasn't slept since the commotion. "How should I know? The entire Council was up and about, though, and they said me husband was needed."
"It be the big building to the south, open to the sky, at the place where the Clan slept on the night Old Man Cavanaugh first found Brogan's shattered arm."
The woman eyes her weaving and sighs. "No one really knows. The legends only say that when Brogan's shattered arm emerged from the underworld, it held the Cavanaugh Stone tight within its fist."
"Look, if ye be that curious in the history of things, ye'd best go to the Guild Hall and talk to Helga." She turns, intent on returning to her weaving.
The woman grinds her teeth in frustration. "There only be so many buildings in the whole village... Bah, fine! It be close by, just on the other side of the mine."
Leave.
"Sorry, me just have questions."
"I'm sorry, I just have some questions."

"Goodbye."
"I need to know 'bout Brogan's Arm."
"I need to know about Brogan's Arm."
"Who your husband be?"
"Who is your husband?"
"Any strangers come through here past while?"
"Have any strangers come through town lately?"
"Me look for Cavanaugh Stone."
"I seek the Cavanaugh Stone."
"Goodbye."
"Tell me 'bout Brogan's Arm."
"Tell me about Brogan's Arm."
"Why you live on surface?"
"Why do you live on the surface?"
"Haunted? Really?"
"Haunted? How so?"
"What you mean by Barrow Dwarves?"
"Barrow Dwarves?"
"Your husband. Me feel like me barely know him."
"Your husband, I feel I still hardly know him."
"How big this clan be?"
"How big is the clan?"
"Mine? Really?"
"What mine?"
"Guild Council? What that be?"
"The Guild Council. What's that?"
"Any strangers come through here past while?"
"Have any strangers come through town lately?"
"Uh, back to my other questions, okay?"
"Sorry, back to my other questions."
"Who know more 'bout these knights?"
"Who can tell me about these knights?"
"What you know of Night Hag?"
"What do you know of the Night Hag?"
"Night Hag be a rag seller?"
"The Night Hag sells you rags?"
"Me look for Cavanaugh Stone."
"I seek the Cavanaugh Stone."
"Trouble? What trouble?"
"What kind of trouble?"
"Barrow site. Where that be?"
"The Barrow site? Where's that?"
"Cavanaugh. That be like Cavanaugh Stone?"
"Cavanaugh. As in the Cavanaugh Stone?"
"Why it be open to sky?"
"Why is it open to the sky?"
"Uh, what the Cavanaugh Stone be?"
"What exactly is the Cavanaugh Stone?"
"But why it called Cavanaugh Stone?"
"But why is it called the Cavanaugh Stone?"
"Uh... Who Brogan be?"
"Who's Brogan?"
"From underworld?"
"From the underworld?"
"How me get to Guild Hall, then?"
"How do I get to the Guild Hall?"
